etymologies: late 19th century (as a noun): abbreviation of sapling (from which such a club was originally made)

definitions: hit with a bludgeon or club

examples.text: it was nice to see someone else get sapped for a change

etymologies: Old English sæp, probably of Germanic origin. The verb (dating from the mid 18th century) is often interpreted as a figurative use of the notion ‘drain the sap from’, but is derived originally from the verb sap, in the sense ‘undermine’

definitions: the fluid, chiefly water with dissolved sugars and mineral salts, that circulates in the vascular system of a plant.
shortDefinitions: fluid which circulates in vascular system of plant

examples.text: the hot, heady days of youth when the sap was rising

definitions: gradually weaken or destroy (a person's strength or power)

examples.text: our energy is being sapped by bureaucrats and politicians
her illness had sapped her of energy and life

etymologies: late 16th century (as a verb in the sense ‘dig a sap or covered trench’): from French saper, from Italian zappare, from zappa ‘spade, spadework’, probably from Arabic sarab ‘underground passage’, or sabora ‘probe a wound, explore’

definitions: a tunnel or trench to conceal an assailant's approach to a fortified place.
shortDefinitions: tunnel or trench to conceal assailant's approach to fortified place

examples.text: having sapped up to the glacis of the city ramparts, Versaillais troops entered the city

definitions: make insecure by removing the foundations of

examples.text: a crazy building, sapped and undermined by the rats

shortDefinitions: make insecure by removing foundations of

definitions: undercut by water or glacial action

examples.text: a valley or channel may have been formed as a result of sapping

shortDefinitions: undercut by water or glacial action

etymologies: early 19th century: abbreviation of dialect sapskull ‘person with a head like sapwood’, from sap (in the sense ‘sapwood’) + skull

examples.text: He fell for it! What a sap!
